    "created_at": "2015-10-09T18:57:19Z",
    "updated_at": "2015-10-09T18:57:19Z",
    "body": "Some thoughts:\n- I think the default behavior when running without `--enable-logging` should be to not output any logs including errors, but still output `console.*` calls. The reason is that the error logs are not really informative. For example on Linux a lot of users (maybe all) get the SUID sandbox message (see screenshot at #1482). It seems pointless to show this info to app users, and developers can run with `--enable-logging` to see it.\n  For Windows we'll need to find a way to dynamiclly set the destination. So `console.*` will print and other direct calls to `LOG` won't print (logging_dest set to none).\n- On Windows, `console.*` calls from renderers are printed to devtools and to cmd. I think it makes more sense that the render calls will print to the devtools console only, and main calls will print to cmd.\n- On Windows, `console.*` calls that are printed to cmd, start with an ugly prefix (e.g. `[11188:1009/211327:INFO:CONSOLE(0)] Some text`). The prefix is due to the usage of Chromium's logging mechanism. It seems it's printed by `LogMessage::Init`. Can we override that during calls to `console.*`? If not, can we just copy the relevent parts and print the calls without a prefix. It really looks weird that when you run `electron --help` or `electron --version` the output includes that prefix.\n\nWhat do you think?\n"
  },
